al life in the great age of sail from the perspective of a surgeon, describing the impact of Enlightenment ideas and new medical techniques, and showing how improved health was a crucial factor in making possible the British fleet's great victories in this period. BRIAN VALE is a maritime historian, whose books include Independence or Death: British sailors and Brazilian Independence (Tauris 1996), A Frigate of King George, Life and Duty on a British Man-of-War (Tauris 2001) and The Audacious Admiral Cochrane (Conway 2004). GRIFFITH EDWARDS, Emeritus Professor at King's College, London, is one of the country's leading experts on addiction. His publications include Alchohol: the Ambiguous Molecule (Penguin 2000) and Matters of Substance (Penguin 2005).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAlcoholismxTreatmentxHistoryy19th century. 0aNeurosesxTreatmentxHistoryy19th century. 0aPhysicianszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aShip physicianszGreat BritainvBiography. 4aEighteenth Century Studies. 4aHistory of Science & Medicine. 4aMaritime History. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Military.2bisacsh  aAddiction.  aHealth and Safety in Mines.  aNaval Surgeon.  aScurvy.  aThomas Trotter.  aTyphus.1 aEdwards, Griffith, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781846159251?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846159251423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846159251/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles